<mermaid-dark-mode-styling>

<title>Mermaid Diagram Dark Mode Styling Standards</title>

<context>
<applies-to>All Mermaid diagrams in academic and technical documentation</applies-to>
</context>

<color-palette>
- Core algorithms: fill:#1a365d, stroke:#63b3ed, stroke-width:2px, color:#e2e8f0
- Main algorithms: fill:#1a202c, stroke:#68d391, stroke-width:2px, color:#e2e8f0
- Helper functions: fill:#4a5568, stroke:#a0aec0, stroke-width:2px, color:#e2e8f0
- Approximation algorithms: fill:#2d3748, stroke:#f6ad55, stroke-width:2px, color:#e2e8f0
- Theoretical results: fill:#553c9a, stroke:#d6bcfa, stroke-width:2px, color:#e2e8f0
- Final outputs: fill:#2f855a, stroke:#9ae6b4, stroke-width:2px, color:#e2e8f0
</color-palette>

<rules>
- Always use stroke-width:2px for visibility and accessibility
- Use light text (#e2e8f0) on all dark backgrounds for readability
- Maintain contrast ratio of at least 4.5:1 for WCAG AA compliance
- Include descriptive legends with consistent styling
- Use semantic color coding where algorithm types have distinct colors
- Apply explicit styling to all nodes, don't rely on defaults
- Group related functions in logical clusters
- Use dotted lines (-..->) for theoretical relationships
- Use solid lines (-->) for direct algorithmic dependencies
</rules>

<examples>
<example type="good">
```mermaid
graph TD
    A[Primary Algorithm] --> B[Secondary Algorithm]
    C[Helper Function] --> A

    style A fill:#1a365d,stroke:#63b3ed,stroke-width:2px,color:#e2e8f0
    style B fill:#1a202c,stroke:#68d391,stroke-width:2px,color:#e2e8f0
    style C fill:#4a5568,stroke:#a0aec0,stroke-width:2px,color:#e2e8f0
```
</example>
</examples>

